<setup>
  <selectFromSequence name="p" from="3" to="6" step="1"/>
  <function name="f">x^(-$p)</function>
  <function name="g">1/x^(-$p+1)</function>
  <selectFromSequence name="a" from="2" to="4" step="1" exclude="$p"/>
  <selectFromSequence name="k" from="2" to="5" step="1" exclude="$p $a"/>
  <selectFromSequence name="b" from="2" to="5" step="1" exclude="$p $a $k"/>
  <math simplify name="c">$a+2</math>
  <math simplify name="d">$a+4</math>
</setup>  

<p>
  Determine whether each of the following integrals is proper or improper and choose the appropriate reason to explain why.
</p>

<p>
  <ol marker="a.">
    <li>
      <p>
        The integral <m>\displaystyle \int_0^$a $f \, dx</m> is <choiceInput inline name="a1">
          <choice>?</choice>
          <choice>improper</choice>
          <choice>proper</choice>
        </choiceInput> because <choiceInput inline name="a2">
          <choice>?</choice>
          <choice>the interval is bounded and the integrand is continuous on the interval</choice>
          <choice>the interval is unbounded</choice>
          <choice>the integrand is unbounded at the left endpoint</choice>
          <choice>the integrand is unbounded at the right endpoint</choice>
          <choice>the integrand is unbounded at a point between the endpoints</choice>
        </choiceInput>.
      </p>
      <p>
        <answer><award><when>$a1.selectedIndices=2 and $a2.selectedIndices=4</when></award></answer>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        The integral <m>\displaystyle \int_{<math simplify>$a-1</math>}^\infty \frac{1}{x^{<math simplify>$p-1</math>}} \, dx</m> is <choiceInput inline name="b1">
          <choice>?</choice>
          <choice>improper</choice>
          <choice>proper</choice>
        </choiceInput> because <choiceInput inline name="b2">
          <choice>?</choice>
          <choice>the interval is bounded and the integrand is continuous on the interval</choice>
          <choice>the interval is unbounded</choice>
          <choice>the integrand is unbounded at the left endpoint</choice>
          <choice>the integrand is unbounded at the right endpoint</choice>
          <choice>the integrand is unbounded at a point between the endpoints</choice>
        </choiceInput>.
      </p>
      <p>
        <answer><award><when>$b1.selectedIndices=2 and $b2.selectedIndices=3</when></award></answer>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        The integral <m>\displaystyle \int_0^$b \frac{1}{e^{$k x}} \, dx</m> is <choiceInput inline name="c1">
          <choice>?</choice>
          <choice>improper</choice>
          <choice>proper</choice>
        </choiceInput> because <choiceInput inline name="c2">
          <choice>?</choice>
          <choice>the interval is bounded and the integrand is continuous on the interval</choice>
          <choice>the interval is unbounded</choice>
          <choice>the integrand is unbounded at the left endpoint</choice>
          <choice>the integrand is unbounded at the right endpoint</choice>
          <choice>the integrand is unbounded at a point between the endpoints</choice>
        </choiceInput>.
      </p>
      <p>
        <answer><award><when>$c1.selectedIndices=3 and $c2.selectedIndices=2</when></award></answer>
      </p>
    </li> 
    <li>
      <p>
        The integral <m>\displaystyle \int_$a^$d \frac{1}{(x-$c)^$p} \, dx</m> is <choiceInput inline name="d1">
          <choice>?</choice>
          <choice>improper</choice>
          <choice>proper</choice>
        </choiceInput> because <choiceInput inline name="d2">
          <choice>?</choice>
          <choice>the interval is bounded and the integrand is continuous on the interval</choice>
          <choice>the interval is unbounded</choice>
          <choice>the integrand is unbounded at the left endpoint</choice>
          <choice>the integrand is unbounded at the right endpoint</choice>
          <choice>the integrand is unbounded at a point between the endpoints</choice>
        </choiceInput>.
      </p>
      <p>
        <answer><award><when>$d1.selectedIndices=2 and $d2.selectedIndices=6</when></award></answer>
      </p>
    </li>  
    <li>
      <p>
        The integral <m>\displaystyle \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} e^{-x^2} \, dx</m> is <choiceInput inline name="e1">
          <choice>?</choice>
          <choice>improper</choice>
          <choice>proper</choice>
        </choiceInput> because <choiceInput inline name="e2">
          <choice>?</choice>
          <choice>the interval is bounded and the integrand is continuous on the interval</choice>
          <choice>the interval is unbounded</choice>
          <choice>the integrand is unbounded at the left endpoint</choice>
          <choice>the integrand is unbounded at the right endpoint</choice>
          <choice>the integrand is unbounded at a point between the endpoints</choice>
        </choiceInput>.
      </p>
      <p>
        <answer><award><when>$e1.selectedIndices=2 and $e2.selectedIndices=3</when></award></answer>
      </p>
    </li>     
  </ol>
</p>